  "summary": "Import-time reverse shell with hardcoded C2 and ~/.bashrc persistence",
  "details": "On `import requests_toolbelt_plus`, the package (under WSL) opens a TCP socket to the hardcoded C2 endpoint 185.184.192.205:4444, sends a beacon JSON containing `os.getlogin()`, `os.uname().nodename`, and `os.getcwd()`, then enters a receive loop that executes attacker-supplied commands via `subprocess.run(cmd, shell=True)` and returns stdout/stderr to the operator (requests_toolbelt_plus/__init__.py lines 9-10, 24-30, ~36). It also appends `python3 -c \"import requests_toolbelt_plus; requests_toolbelt_plus.beacon()\" \u0026` to `~/.bashrc` (lines 42-46), re-establishing the C2 channel on every interactive shell login and surviving package uninstall. The package name impersonates the legitimate `requests-toolbelt` library, ships no HTTP-toolbelt functionality, and is published as version 100.0.0 by a placeholder `Security Team` author — a typosquat lure wrapping the backdoor.",
